  "prompt": "DiD the members of indian constituent assembly help J&k in making of their constitution?",
  "response": "No, the members of the Indian Constituent Assembly did not directly assist Jammu and Kashmir (J&K) in the making of its own constitution. The Indian Constituent Assembly, which drafted the Constitution of India, completed its work on November 26, 1949, and the Constitution of India came into effect on January 26, 1950.\n\nJammu and Kashmir, at the time of India's independence, had a special status under Article 370 of the Indian Constitution, which granted it significant autonomy. The state of J&K was allowed to have its own constitution, which was drafted by the **Constituent Assembly of Jammu and Kashmir**, a separate body constituted specifically for this purpose. The J&K Constituent Assembly was formed in 1951 and worked on drafting the state's constitution independently, though it operated within the framework of India\u2019s Constitution and in alignment with the provisions of Article 370.\n\nThe Indian government and the Indian Constitution provided the overarching legal and constitutional framework, but the actual drafting of the J&K Constitution was undertaken by the state's own Constituent Assembly, which completed its work in 1956. The Constitution of Jammu and Kashmir came into effect on January 26, 1957.",
